# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Terminal gateway configuration. Copy to `.env` (gitignored) and edit.
# The gateway loads this via `node --env-file-if-exists=.env`.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ---- Bind / network ----
# PORT=3007
# HOST=127.0.0.1
# Comma-separated browser origins allowed for CSRF/CSWSH checks.
# ALLOWED_ORIGINS=http://localhost:3000,http://localhost:3007
# Set to 1 when behind a trusted reverse proxy (honors X-Forwarded-For, marks
# the session cookie Secure).
# TRUST_PROXY=1

# ---- Auth (single user; see docs/DEPLOYMENT.md) ----
# GATEWAY_AUTH_USER=admin
# Production: a scrypt hash from `pnpm --filter @sparklab/terminal-gateway hash-password`.
# GATEWAY_AUTH_PASSWORD_HASH=scrypt$...
# Dev/test only: plaintext password, hashed once at startup.
# GATEWAY_AUTH_PASSWORD=changeme

# ---- Web Push notifications ("your job finished") ----
# Generate a keypair ONCE with:
#   pnpm --filter @sparklab/terminal-gateway generate-vapid
# then paste the two keys below. Keep them STABLE — rotating invalidates every
# existing browser subscription. If these are absent the push feature is simply
# disabled (endpoints report not-configured, the poll loop never starts) and the
# gateway boots and behaves exactly as before. See docs/PUSH-NOTIFICATIONS-PLAN.md.
# VAPID_PUBLIC_KEY=
# VAPID_PRIVATE_KEY=
# Contact URI (mailto: or https:) the push service can reach you at.
# VAPID_SUBJECT=mailto:admin@example.com
